  "docs": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Compute the N-dimensional inverse discrete Fourier Transform."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Summary"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "This function computes the inverse of the N-dimensional discrete\nFourier Transform over any number of axes in an M-dimensional array by\nmeans of the Fast Fourier Transform (FFT).  In other words,\n"
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "ifftn(fftn(a)) == a"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " to within numerical accuracy.\nFor a description of the definitions and conventions used, see "
              },
              {
                "external_url": "https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.fft.html",
                "href": "",
                "kind": "link",
                "target": "fft",
                "text": "fnp.fft"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The input, analogously to "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "ifft"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ", should be ordered in the same way as is\nreturned by "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "fftn"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ", i.e. it should have the term for zero frequency\nin all axes in the low-order corner, the positive frequency terms in the\nfirst half of all axes, the term for the Nyquist frequency in the middle\nof all axes and the negative frequency terms in the second half of all\naxes, in order of decreasingly negative frequency."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Extended Summary"
      },
